## Phase 3: Always-On Voice with Wake Word

### [MODIFY] [main.js](file:///c:/Users/omara/ai-assistant/electron/main.js) + [panel.html](file:///c:/Users/omara/ai-assistant/electron/panel.html)

Current: user clicks "Speak" button → records → sends to Whisper → agent processes → TTS response.

**Target:** Always-on mic → wake word "Jarvis" → auto-activate → continuous conversation → auto-deactivate after silence.

**Implementation:**
1. **Continuous VAD (Voice Activity Detection):** Use Web Audio API `AnalyserNode` to detect when the user starts/stops speaking
2. **Wake word detection:** Simple local approach — stream audio to Whisper in small chunks (2-3 sec), check if transcription contains "Jarvis"/"hey Jarvis". When detected, switch to active listening mode
3. **Active session:** Once activated, keep recording until 3 seconds of silence, then process
4. **Toggle:** Tray icon toggle for always-on vs manual mode

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Wake word detection using Whisper costs ~$0.006/minute. For always-on, that's ~$0.36/hour. 
> Alternative: use a local wake word library like [Porcupine](https://picovoice.ai/platform/porcupine/) (free tier: 3 custom wake words) for zero-cost always-on, then switch to Whisper only when activated.

### [MODIFY] [agent.js](file:///c:/Users/omara/ai-assistant/src/agent.js)

**Concurrent speech + action:**
- Current flow: [_runLoop()](file:///c:/Users/omara/ai-assistant/src/agent.js#297-402) returns text ONLY after all tool iterations are done
- New flow: emit [onProgress({ type: 'speech', text })](file:///c:/Users/omara/ai-assistant/electron/main.js#276-277) immediately when Claude returns text, WHILE tools continue executing
- The renderer speaks this text via TTS immediately, agent keeps working

